50	// A representation of a set of DispatchKeys. A DispatchKeySet contains both
51	// "functionality" bits and "backend bits", and every tensor holds its own
52	// DispatchKeySet. The Dispatcher implements multiple dispatch by grabbing the
53	// keyset on every input tensor, or’ing them together, and dispatching to a
54	// specific piece of functionality. The functionality bits are *ordered*. When
55	// multiple functionality bits are set, we use the highest priority
56	// functionality. Similarly, multiple backend bits can theoretically be set if
57	// you call an operator with multiple tensors from difference devices (e.g. CPU
58	// and CUDA), although support for mixed device dispatch is limited (the only
59	// kernels that gracefully handle mixed device inputs for now are cuda kernels
60	// that take in a scalar cpu tensor).
61	
62	// A representation of a set of DispatchKeys.  A tensor may have multiple
63	// tensor type ids, e.g., a Variable tensor can also be a CPU tensor; the
64	// DispatchKeySet specifies what type ids apply.  The internal representation is
65	// as a 64-bit bit set (this means only 64 tensor type ids are supported).
66	//
67	// As mentioned above, DispatchKeys are ordered; thus, we can ask questions like
68	// "what is the highest priority DispatchKey in the set"?  (The set itself is
69	// not ordered; two sets with the same ids will always have the ids ordered in
70	// the same way.)
71	//
72	// Note [DispatchKeySet Internal Representation]
73	// Internally, dispatch keys are packed into 64-bit DispatchKeySet objects
74	// that get passed around at runtime.
75	// However, there isn't necessarily a 1-to-1 mapping between bits in the keyset
76	// and individual dispatch keys.
77	//
78	// First: why do we have this distinction, and why not map every dispatch key
79	// directly to a bit? This is mostly because we have several types of
80	// functionalities that different backends would like to customize. For example,
81	// we have:
82	// - "Dense":     CPU, CUDA, XLA, ... (~12 keys)
83	// - "Sparse":    SparseCPU, SparseCUDA, ...
84	// - "SparseCsr": SparseCsrCPU, SparseCsrCUDA, ...
85	// - "Quantized": QuantizedCPU, QuantizedCUDA, QuantizedXLA, ...
86	// - "Autograd":  AutogradCPU, AutogradCUDA, Autograd XLA, ...
87	// The problem is that total number of keys grows quadratically with [#
88	// backends] x [# functionalities], making it very difficult to map each key
89	// directly to a bit in a bitset without dramatically increasing the size of the
90	// bitset over time.
91	//
92	// The two enums (BackendComponent and DispatchKey) can be divided roughly into
93	// 5 categories.
94	//
95	// (1) "Building block" keys
96	//    (a) backends: Everything in the BackendComponent enum (e.g. CPUBit,
97	//    CUDABit) (b) functionalities: (per-backend) functionality-bit DispatchKeys
98	//    (e.g. AutogradFunctionality, SparseCsr, Sparse, Dense)
99	// (2) "Runtime" keys
100	//    (a) "non-customizable backends" (e.g. FPGA)
101	//    (b) "non-customizable functionalities" (e.g. Functionalize)
102	//    (c) "per-backend instances of customizable functionalities" (e.g. CPU,
103	//    SparseCPU, AutogradCPU)
104	// (3) "Alias" DispatchKeys (see Note [Alias Dispatch Keys])
105	//
106	// (1) Building block keys always correspond to individual bits in a
107	// DispatchKeySet. They can also be combined in a DispatchKeySet to form actual
108	// runtime keys. e.g.
109	//     auto dense_cpu_ks = DispatchKeySet({DispatchKey::CPUBit,
110	//     DispatchKey::Dense});
111	//     // The keyset has the runtime dense-cpu key.
112	//     dense_cpu_ks.has(DispatchKey::CPU);
113	//     // And it contains the building block keys too.
114	//     dense_cpu_ks.has(DispatchKey::CPUBit);
115	//     dense_cpu_ks.has(DispatchKey::Dense);
116	//
117	// Not every backend and not every functionality counts as a "building block
118	// key". This is mostly to give us more levers to pull in the design space.
119	// Backend keys and functionality keys that count as "building blocks" will
120	// contribute to a full cross product of functionality that can be overridden.
121	//
122	// For example, right now we have at least 12 "backend" building
123	// blocks (CPU, CUDA, XLA, ...) and at least 5 "functionality"
124	// building blocks (Dense, Sparse, SparseCsr, Quantized,
125	// AutogradFunctionality, ...). These keys together allow every
126	// dispatcher operator to be customized in up to 12*4 different
127	// ways. Each of those requires a slot in the operator table of every
128	// dispatcher operator.  Not every piece of functionality necessarily
129	// needs to be customizable per-backend, and not every backend
130	// necessarily needs to be able to customize every type of
131	// functionality.
132	//
133	//
134	// (2) Every runtime key corresponds directly to a slot in an operator's runtime
135	// dispatch table, and you can directly register kernels to a runtime dispatch
136	// key.
137	//
138	// For per-backend functionalities like "Dense" or "AutogradFunctionality",
139	// you can think of the corresponding runtime dispatch keys as "instances" of
140	// that functionality, per backend. E.g. "CPU", "CUDA", "XLA", etc. are all
141	// runtime instances of the "Dense" building block key.
142	
143	// (2a) and (2b) are represented identically in the DispatchKeySet logic:
144	// - backend-agnostic functionalities (e.g. FuncTorchBatched) are NOT
145	// customizable per backend.
146	//   In order to do so, we'd need to promote it to a per-backend functionality
147	//   "building block" key.
148	// - non-customizable backends (e.g. FPGA) can NOT customize existing
149	// functionality like Sparse, Autograd, etc.
150	//   In order to do so, we'd need to promote it to a backend "building block"
151	//   key.
152	//
153	// In both cases, these keys directly correspond to runtime slots in the
154	// operator table.
155	//
156	//
157	// (3) "Alias" keys
158	// See Note [Alias Dispatch Keys]
159	//
160	// Final note: for anyone making future changes to the Dispatcher +
161	// DispatchKeySet internals, there's a closed PR with a basic
162	// python-implementation of the Dispatcher that might be useful in quickly
163	// testing out and validating changes. See it at
164	// https://github.com/pytorch/pytorch/pull/68743
