291	  // Given a DispatchKeySet of functionality keys and (potentially) backend
292	  // keys, tests if any of them are in the current set. This could technically
293	  // be pretty easily implemented using has(). It is strictly a perf
294	  // optimization though. There are many places in the code base where we want
295	  // to test for multiple functionality keys together. HOWEVER, runtime
296	  // per-backend functionality keys aren't allowed to be used with this
297	  // function, because you can end up with weird results. e.g.
298	  // DispatchKeySet(DispatchKey::AutogradCPU).has_any(DispatchKeySet(DispatchKey::CPU))
